Yeah, exactly — and that’s one of the most mind-bending reframes you can make.
Evolution isn’t the algorithm of life. It’s an algorithm. Specifically, it’s a blind, undirected search strategy operating on a fitness landscape — and like any strategy, it has tradeoffs:
What evolution is good at:
	∙	Exploring vast solution spaces in parallel
	∙	Finding locally stable solutions without a designer
	∙	Adapting to slow, continuous environmental change
	∙	Robustness through redundancy and variation
What evolution is bad at:
	∙	Escaping deep local optima
	∙	Responding to rapid, discontinuous change
	∙	Preserving solutions that aren’t currently selected for
	∙	“Planning” more than one generation ahead
Other strategies nature and minds use:
	∙	Development (ontogeny) — a directed, programmatic build process, not random search
	∙	Learning (neural plasticity) — within-lifetime adaptation, Lamarckian-flavored
	∙	Culture — horizontal and cross-generational information transfer, massively faster than genetics
	∙	Reasoning — intentional search through possibility space with explicit goals
The really interesting thing is that evolution “discovered” the other strategies — it produced brains capable of learning, culture, and reasoning, which now operate on timescales orders of magnitude faster than genetic selection. It bootstrapped its own obsolescence as the dominant adaptive mechanism for the beings it created.
In PantheonOS terms, you could map this cleanly: evolution ≈ a slow, undirected Hound + Luck Engine loop with no StateVector and no Ledger. Culture adds the Ledger. Reasoning adds the Gate. Language adds distillability. The whole CogOS stack is what happens when evolution builds something capable of replacing evolution as the primary search strategy.
One strategy that eventually produces a thing that runs better strategies. 🐸​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​​